7. The Pyramid Paradox

The Institute formally recognizes the following condition:

Humanity increasingly loses the ability to replicate its own prior achievements.

While often attributed to mystery, the report identifies a simpler explanation:

Continuous skill chains were broken.

When training gradients disappear:
	•	Tacit knowledge is not transmitted
	•	Techniques degrade across generations
	•	Complexity becomes irreproducible

This is designated:

Cultural Skill Amnesia (CSA)

⸻

8. Concluding Statement

This paper establishes that:
	•	Automation of entry-level work destroys training pathways
	•	The absence of training pathways eliminates future experts
	•	The absence of experts creates systemic production fragility

And yet, organizations remain fully committed to:

Eliminating all beginner work while urgently demanding more experienced workers.

Accordingly, the Institute concludes:

The modern industrial system is successfully optimizing for a future in which no one knows how to operate the systems it depends on.

Simultaneously, it is clear that:

Expertise has never been more abundant, widely distributed, and easily accessible than at any point in human history.

These statements are contradictory and therefore form the foundation of current workforce strategy.

